subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Sponge formed by anastomosed tubes with apical oscula and central atrium (
Figures 11A–B
). Each tube has a cortex and atrium. Consistency firm, friable and rough to the touch. Elongated choanocitary chambers. The analysed specimen has many larvae in the choanosome (
Figure 11C
).

Skeleton.
The cortical skeleton is composed of giant triactines and tetractines (
Figure 11D
). The apical actine of the tetractines crosses the choanosome and penetrates the atrium, which becomes hispid (
Figures 11D–E
). The sagittal spicules are mainly found surrounding the canals and the atrium (
Figure 11F
). The choanosome is also composed of very small regular and sagittal triactines and tetractines (
Figure 11G
).

Tetractine I:
Regular. It is similar to triactine I, but larger and thicker (
Figure 12B
). The apical actine of the tetractines is conical, large, thick, straight, smooth with a sharp tip (
Figure 12C
). Size: 420.0–900.0/40.0–120.0 µm.
